    -Atom radial functions are often expressed as phi(r) = 1/r * Pnl(r)  where Pnl(r) is then expanded in some basis set.
        Then the overlap S_ab = integral(Phi_a*Phi_b*r^2*dr) = integral(Pnl_a*Pnl_b*dr).
        Currently the qchem package handles all basis sets as phi(r) = Pnl(r) without the 1/r
        Starting with splines we should add support for 1/r * Pnl(r)
        This might enhance numerical stability for N>40 basis functions.
        The problem is to decide a naming convention for each case:
            phi(r) = 1/r * Pnl(r) name= BSpline_r
            phi(r) =       Pnl(r) name= BSpline
        Done: -In order to implement this we will need to support <a|1/r|b> and <a|1/r^2|b> integrals.  These are not directly
         supported by c++ BSpline package.  only operator X<n> where n>=0 are supported.
        Done: -We can do the integrals with numerical recipes gauleg function which calculates sets {x},{w} for quadrature integration.
        Fixed: -However it seems that BilinearForm{X<2>{}}(a,b)*FourPi; and gauleg.Integrate(x2,a,b)*FourPi; are giving different results
         especially near the origin.
         -gauleg was using order K+2*l,  changed to K+3 and error disapeared.
        Goals:
        1) Get BilinearForm{X<2>{}}(a,b) == gl.Integrate(x2,a,b) to machine accuracy
            K=9 weight x^0: 378 error>1e-14, max=2.24e-12, weight x^2: 382 error>1e-14, max=5.77e-12
            k=8 weight x^0: 234 error>1e-14, max=6.37e-13, weight x^2: 561 error>1e-14, max=1.22e-12
            K=7 weight x^0: 241 error>1e-14, max=2.22e-13, weight x^2: 212 error>1e-14, max=3.73e-13
            K=6 weight x^0: 226 error>1e-14, max=6.17e-14, weight x^2: 160 error>1e-14, max=9.21e-14
            K=5 weight x^0: 229 error>1e-14, max=3.06e-14, weight x^2: 69  error>1e-14, max=7.87e-14
            K=4 weight x^0: 3   error>1e-14, max=2.22e-14, weight x^2: 201 error>1e-14, max=1.49e-14
            K=3 weight x^0: 1   error>1e-14, max=1.42e-14, weight x^2: 3   error>1e-14, max=1.29e-14
            Errors between BSpline package and gauleg integration grow rapidly for K>~4
        Done: 2) Check all the other required integrals.
        Done: 3) Support both basis set options above 1) phi(r) = 1/r * Pnl(r) and 2) phi(r) = Pnl(r)
        4) Verify comments from Saito: To construct the B-spline set for atomic calculations, the knot
            sequence must be generated in [0, R] with K-fold multiple end-
            points. Since the first and last terms of such B-splines are nonzero
            at r = 0 and at r = R, respectively, they were removed from the basis
            set in order to satisfy the boundary conditions. An N-term B-spline
            set {Bi,K}i=2,. . .,N+1 is thereby obtained...
            -Saito uses Rmin=10^-4=0.0001  qchem can't handle this, even for Hydrogen!!
            -Rmin=0.01 workes well for Z=1..10.
            -Toughest atoms in the first two rows for virial ratio Are:
                N=100,R=[0.01,40]  Li,B, O
                N=50 ,R=[0.01,40]  Li,B, O
        4.5) Add V/K-2 to convergence criteria.

        Done: 5) Get He working to high precision.  In particular fabs(V/K+2) < 1e-11
        6) Refactor BSpline and BSpine_r to minimize duplicated code.  Isolate weight functions wp, wm.
        7) Try to run atoms 2->118 and compared E, Eo and <r> moments.
            

    -re-imagine Electron configurations
        -How about map<Irrep_QNs,size_t> Occs to track all occupations.
        -Yes this is what we need
        -We need to build this list from ElCounts=
            int N [LMax+1]; //Total N[l]
            int Nf[LMax+1]; //Full shell or core, N[l]
            int Nv[LMax+1]; //Valance shell N[l].  He is considered to have no valance electrons ... all are core.
            int Nu[LMax+1]; //# of unpaired electrons for a given l.
        -if l=0, then no magnetic splitting. 
            assert((N+Nu)%2) 
            Occs[Up,s]=(N+Nu)/2
            Occs[Dn,s]=(N-Nu)/2
            or:
            Occs[Up,s]=Nf/2+Nu
            Occs[Dn,s]=Nf/2
        -if l>0  now we need to worry about magnetic splitting
            Npair=(Nv-Nu)/2 (for l=1 this 0,1,2)
            m_unpaired has Nu m values, g_unpaired=Nu
            m_paired gets the remainder, g_paired=g-Nu
            n_levels=Nf/g2
            Occs[Up,Ylm_paired]=n_levels*g_paired+Npair
            Occs[Dn,Ylm_paired]=n_levels*g_paired+Npair
            Occs[Up,Ylm_unpaired]=n_levels*g_unpaired+Nu


